<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Differs from its only congener known from the Caucasus, 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. spathulatum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="spathulatum">M. (s. str.) spathulatum</taxonomicName>
(Lohmander, 1936), mainly by the colour pattern: body uniformly dark with an orange to dark red mid-dorsal line, vs. body with a light yellow to ochre dorsum divided by a black axial line in 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. spathulatum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="spathulatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. spathulatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; and by the promere having mostly parallel side margins, ending with a flat apex, vs. the same significantly tapering all the way to a narrowly rounded apex in 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. spathulatum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="spathulatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. spathulatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="records from the caucasus">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Records from the Caucasus.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Russia</emphasis>
: Environs of Novorossiysk (
<bibRefCitation author="Lignau, N" journalOrPublisher="Odessa]" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="82 - 149" refId="B58" refString="Lignau, N, 1903. [Myriapods of the Black Sea coast of the Caucasus]. Die Myriopoden am Kaukasischen Schwarzmeerufer. Memoires de la Societe Imperiale des Naturalistes de la Nouvelle-Russie. [Zapiski Imperatorskogo Novorossiyskogo obshchestva estestvoispytateley. Odessa] 25 (1): 82 - 149" title="[Myriapods of the Black Sea coast of the Caucasus]. Die Myriopoden am Kaukasischen Schwarzmeerufer. Memoires de la Societe Imperiale des Naturalistes de la Nouvelle-Russie. [Zapiski Imperatorskogo Novorossiyskogo obshchestva estestvoispytateley." volume="25" year="1903">Lignau 1903</bibRefCitation>
); 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Georgia</emphasis>
: AR Abkhazia, Pitsunda (
<bibRefCitation author="Issajev, WM" journalOrPublisher="Trudy Imperatorskogo Sankt-Peterburgskogo obshchestva estestvoispytateley" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="292 - 310" refId="B46" refString="Issajev, WM, 1911. [Observations of millipedes Diplopoda on the Black Sea coast of the Caucasus]. Trudy Imperatorskogo Sankt-Peterburgskogo obshchestva estestvoispytateley 42 (1): 292 - 310" title="[Observations of millipedes Diplopoda on the Black Sea coast of the Caucasus]." volume="42" year="1911">Issajev 1911</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">General distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Central and southwestern parts of the Balkan Peninsula, northwestern Caucasus.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Apart from the records from the Caucasus region, 
<bibRefCitation author="Lignau, N" journalOrPublisher="Odessa]" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="82 - 149" refId="B58" refString="Lignau, N, 1903. [Myriapods of the Black Sea coast of the Caucasus]. Die Myriopoden am Kaukasischen Schwarzmeerufer. Memoires de la Societe Imperiale des Naturalistes de la Nouvelle-Russie. [Zapiski Imperatorskogo Novorossiyskogo obshchestva estestvoispytateley. Odessa] 25 (1): 82 - 149" title="[Myriapods of the Black Sea coast of the Caucasus]. Die Myriopoden am Kaukasischen Schwarzmeerufer. Memoires de la Societe Imperiale des Naturalistes de la Nouvelle-Russie. [Zapiski Imperatorskogo Novorossiyskogo obshchestva estestvoispytateley." volume="25" year="1903">Lignau (1903)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Issajev, WM" journalOrPublisher="Trudy Imperatorskogo Sankt-Peterburgskogo obshchestva estestvoispytateley" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="292 - 310" refId="B46" refString="Issajev, WM, 1911. [Observations of millipedes Diplopoda on the Black Sea coast of the Caucasus]. Trudy Imperatorskogo Sankt-Peterburgskogo obshchestva estestvoispytateley 42 (1): 292 - 310" title="[Observations of millipedes Diplopoda on the Black Sea coast of the Caucasus]." volume="42" year="1911">Issajev (1911)</bibRefCitation>
both mentioned that 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. hercules" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="hercules">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. hercules</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was rather common across the Crimean Peninsula, and although neither of them documented those reports with gonopod drawings, the very characteristic habitus of this species alone makes misidentification very unlikely: it has a dark grey to blackish body with an orange to dark red axial line, while the other two congeners occurring at the northeastern Black Sea coast, 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. spathulatum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="spathulatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. spathulatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Lohmander, 1936) and 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. tauricum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="tauricum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. tauricum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Attems, C" journalOrPublisher="Arkiv foer zoologi" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 16" publicationUrl="https://archive.org/details/biostor-98986" refId="B8" refString="Attems, C, 1907. Myriopoden aus der Krim und dem Kaukasus von Dr. A. Stuxberg gesammelt. Arkiv foer zoologi 3 (25): 1 - 16, https://archive.org/details/biostor-98986" title="Myriopoden aus der Krim und dem Kaukasus von Dr. A. Stuxberg gesammelt." url="https://archive.org/details/biostor-98986" volume="3" year="1907">Attems 1907</bibRefCitation>
), are both characterised by a black axial line on a light yellow to ochre (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lohmander" baseAuthorityYear="1936" class="Diplopoda" family="Julidae" genus="Megaphyllum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megaphyllum spathulatum" order="Julida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spathulatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Megaphyllum spathulatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) or brown-grey (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Attems" baseAuthorityYear="1907" class="Diplopoda" family="Julidae" genus="Megaphyllum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megaphyllum tauricum" order="Julida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tauricum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Megaphyllum tauricum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) dorsum. Also bearing in mind the disjunct Balkan-Caucasian distribution of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Timotheew" baseAuthorityYear="1897" class="Diplopoda" family="Julidae" genus="Byzantorhopalum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Byzantorhopalum rossicum" order="Julida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rossicum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Byzantorhopalum rossicum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see Vagalinski and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Lázanyi">Lazanyi</normalizedToken>
2018), as well as the Crimean endemic 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. tauricum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="tauricum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. tauricum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a very close sibling of the Balkan 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. rhodopinum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="rhodopinum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. rhodopinum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Verhoeff, 1928), 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. hercules" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="hercules">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. hercules</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be another example of this pattern, the lack of more recent samples from the Caucasus being due to its rarity in the region.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
